Explorer Concepts Dashboard¶

This dashboard is designed to help you investigate and visualise concepts extracted from the Global Stock Take (GST) data via explorer.

In [1]:

from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS

import numpy as np

concept = "fossil-fuels"
df_concepts = pd.read_excel(concepts_path / concept / "output_with_metadata.xlsx")
df_spans = pd.read_csv(concepts_path / concept / "spans.csv")

0 Methane mitigation opportunities by sector include:\n Energy Sector Methane. Energy sector fugitive methane emissions result from opera-\ntions in the oil and natural gas sector and the coal mining sector. In some cases, a large\nproportion of oil and gas methane emissions come from a small number of sources. Me-\nthane mitigation measures in oil and natural gas typically fall into three categories:\nequipment modifications or upgrades; changes in operational practices, including di-\nrected inspection, repair and maintenance (DI&M); and installation of new equipment\n[35]. Abatement measures are available to mitigate emissions associated with a variety\nof system components, including compressors, engines, dehydrators, pneumatic con-\ntrols, pipelines, storage tanks, wells, and others. Commercially-available mitigation tech-\nnologies can also recover and reduce CH4 emissions from coal mining operations. These\nreduction technologies consist of one or more of the following primary components: a\ndrainage and recovery system to remove CH4 from the underground coal seam, an end\nuse application for the gas recovered from the drainage system, and/or a ventilation air\nmethane (VAM) recovery or mitigation system [35]. The CH4 mitigation potential from\nthe energy sector at $100/tCOe is 144 million metric tons of carbon dioxide equivalent\n(MtCOe), or approximately 43% of 2030 energy sector non-CO GHG emissions, and re-\nmains an important source of potential mitigation through 2050.\n Waste Methane. Landfills produce CH4 and other landfill gases through the natural pro-\ncess of bacterial decomposition of organic waste under anaerobic conditions. Landfill\ngases are generated over a period of several decades, with flows usually beginning\nwithin 2 years of disposal. Abatement options to control landfill emissions are grouped\ninto three categories: (1) collection and flaring, (2) landfill gas (LFG) utilization systems, 1 1 1 1 CCLW.gst.652.652 US_accessibleLTS2021 application/pdf False Figure 14: 2050 Methane Abatement Potential in the United States. This figure shows\nsources of methane abatement potential in 2030 in the United States [36]. This mar-\nginal abatement cost curve indicates the price at which methane mitigation from vari-\nous sources of methane are cost-effective. This figure does not include additional\nabatement that can be achieved by reducing the underlying activities that drive emis-\nsions. These additional reductions from activity driver changes are included in the GCAM\nmodeling and reflected in Figure 12. Approximately 100 MtCO2e in methane emissions\ncan be abated at negative cost, primarily from oil and natural gas sources, but also with\nsome contributions from coal mining, landfills, and livestock. Approximately an addi-\ntional 125 MtCO2e can be abated at ~$50/tCO2e or less, primarily from oil and natural\ngas and livestock sources. Approximately an additional 50 MtCO2e can be abated at\n~$100/tCO2e or less, from livestock and oil and natural gas sources. A remaining ap-\nproximately 50 MtCO2e can only be abated at prices ~$150/tCO2e or higher. and (3) enhanced waste diversion practices (e.g., recycling and reuse programs) [35].\nWithin the waste category, wastewater treatment is the second most important source\nof non-CO GHGs. Methane emissions in wastewater treatment could be significantly\nreduced by 2050 through currently available mitigation options, such as anaerobic bio-\nmass digesters and centralized wastewater treatment facilities. Improved operational\npractices, such as controlling dissolved oxygen levels during treatment or limiting oper-\nating system upsets, can also help reduce NO emissions from wastewater treatment\n[35]. 1 processing activities. The extraction, production,\nprocessing, or transportation of fuels involve\nsubstantial quantity of methane emissions to the\natmosphere. Oil and natural gas systems are\npotentially very complex and diverse. Two major issues\nconcerning the reported fugitive emissions from oil\nand gas systems are: (i) the generally poor quality and\ncompleteness of available venting and flaring data; (ii)\nthe fact that much of the infrastructure contributing to\nequipment leaks is at minor facilities for which\nstatistics are either unavailable or incomplete (e.g.\nwell site facilities and field facilities). Fugitive\nemissions consist of CH, mostly however CO, is also\nemitted from the coal mines. It is the first time that the\ngovernment actually started to use coal for electricity\ngeneration. 2 Upstream exploration and exploitation of primary energy sources:\nEmissions from exploration, mining and all related activities supporting the\nprocesses, products storage and transportation.\nFugitive emissions resulting from processes such as flaring, venting and lea\nconnecting and storage modules of crude oil and natural gas handling.\nFugitive emissions of methane during coal mining.\nTransformation of primary energy sources into more usable energy forms in refineries\nplants:\nEmissions from flaring, cracking of crude oil into component fractions an\ncombustion to support these activities. It also involves fuel combustions\nplants for steam, heat for use in electricity generation.\nTransmission and distribution of fuels:\nFuel combustion to generate electrical power for pipelines.\nFuel combustion in transport trucks / vessels.\nFugitive emissions during transmission and distribution.\nUse of fuels in stationary and mobile applications:\nFuel combustion in the transport sector.\nOn-site power generation plants.\nIndustrial use for heat generation and to power equipment. 1 1 1 1 CCLW.gst.511.511 NIGERIA20NIR120-20First20National20GHG20Inventory20Report20 application/pdf False The activities within the Energy sector, leading to these emissions occur in the different segments of\nactivities. Emissions are associated with energy production, processing for converting primary fuels into\nsecondary fuels, transportation and storage as well as end products utilization. Fuel combustion activities\nis one of such end products utilization and involves both primary and secondary fuels. Upstream to these\nare extraction, refining, transportation and storage of primary and secondary hydrocarbons. The activities\nresponsible for emissions are: Nigeria is a producer and exporter of crude oil, petroleum products and natural gas and produces coal for\ndomestic use. Whenever local production cannot meet local demand, the country resort to importation\nto bridge the gap between demand and supply. The main secondary sources of liquid, biomass and\ngaseous fuels are diesel, gasoline, Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG), kerosene, Automotive Gas Oil (AGO) /\nDiesel, Aviation Turbine Kerosene (ATK), fuel wood, charcoal, bagasse, vegetal wastes, natural gas and\nhousehold kerosene (HHK) amongst others. Natural gas is utilized for public power generation with diesel\nand Fuel Oil (FO) as back-up fuels as well as in industries for heat and own-use power generation.\nTransport fuels include gasoline and AGO / Diesel for road transportation, inland water navigation and\nrailway, ATK for civil aviation and FO for international water navigation. Fuels consumed in the\nCommercial / Institutional and Residential sectors include HHK for cooking and lighting, LPG for cooking,\ngasoline and AGO / Diesel for auto-generation of electricity and biomass fuels (fuel wood and charcoal). 3 of passenger cars are more than 20 years old). This phenomenon was aggravated\nmore by the high taxation imposed on vehicles with engines over 2000 cm.\nFugitive emissions from coal mining and handling (CH4 emissions) are a key\ncategory. CH4 emissions from the mining of lignite in 2020 account for 0.4% of\ntotal GHG emissions. A 72.9% decrease for the period 1990-2020 is observed.\nThis decrease is attributed to the gradual phasing-out of lignite-fired power\nplants in recent years. According to the NECP of Greece, there is an undergoing\nplan for the phasing-out of all but one lignite-plants by 2023. The remaining\nplant will be converted to NG by 2028.\nGHG emissions from activities related to primary production (extraction),\nprocessing, storage and transmission/ distribution of crude oil, petroleum\nproducts and natural gas included in Fugitive emissions, in 2020 accounted for\n0.26% of total GHG emissions. Overall, emissions in 2020 increased by about\n71.2% compared to 1990 levels. The parameters affecting GHG emissions trends\nfrom oil and natural gas are the gradual penetration of natural gas in the Greek\nenergy system and the domestic production of crude oil and natural gas. The\nintroduction of natural gas in the Greek energy system started in 1996 and at the\nmoment its development is in progress. The domestic production of crude oil and\nnatural gas present a continuous decreasing trend and as a result emissions from\nventing and flaring are decreasing.\nEmissions from Industrial Processes and Product use in 2020 accounted for\n14.01% of the total emissions (excluding LULUCF) and decreased by 7.02%\ncompared to 1990 levels. Emissions from IPPU are characterized by intense\nfluctuations during the period 1990 - 2020 reaching a minimum value of 10.39\nMt CO2 eq in 2011 and a maximum value of 16.41 Mt CO2 eq in 1999. The low\nvalue for 2011 is directly related to the effects of the economic recession\nwhereas the maximum value is attributed to changes in industrial production and\nespecially in HCFC-22 production. It should be noted that had it not been for the\nconsumption of f-gases subcategory, the decrease of the recent years would have\nbeen much deeper.\nEmissions from Agriculture that accounted for 10.48% of total emissions in\n2020 (without LULUCF), decreased by approximately 23.59% compared to\n1990 levels. Emissions reduction is mainly due to the reduction of N2O\nemissions from agricultural soils, because of the reduction in the use of synthetic\nnitrogen fertilizers and animal population. The decrease in the use of synthetic\nnitrogen fertilizers is attributed to the increase of organic farming, the high price\nof fertilizers and the impact of initiatives to promote good practice in fertilizer\nuse. The changes of the rest determining parameters of GHG emissions from the\nsector (e.g. crops production etc.) have a minor effect on GHG emissions trend.\nEmissions from the Waste Sector (6.52% of the total emissions, without\nLULUCF), increased by approximately 0.32% from 1990. Living standards\nimprovement resulted in an increase of the generated waste and thus of\nemissions since 1990. However, the increase of recycling along with the\nexploitation of the biogas produced limits the increase of methane emissions. At\nthe same time, emissions from wastewater handling have considerably\ndecreased, due to the continuous increase of the population served by aerobic\nwastewater handling facilities.\nThe Land Use, Land-Use Change and Forestry sector was a net sink of\ngreenhouse gases during the period 1990 - 2020. The sink capacity of the\nLULUCF sector fluctuates between -0.13 Mt CO2 eq. and -4.03 Mt CO2 eq.,\nshowing fluctuations in trend. This is the result of the decrease of the sink 1 1 1 1 CCLW.gst.508.508 NC8_BR5_Greece application/pdf False The living standards improvement resulted in an increase of energy consumption\nand particularly electricity consumption (mainly in the residential - tertiary\nsector), passenger cars ownership and transportation activity. The increase of\nelectricity consumption led not only to the increase of direct emissions (due to\ncombustion for electricity generation) but also of fugitive methane emissions\nfrom lignite mining.\nAt the same time total CO2 emissions per electricity produced have decreased\nmainly as a result of the introduction of the natural gas and RES into the\nelectricity system. It should be mentioned that the availability of hydropower has\na significant effect to emissions trends. For instance, the significant increase of\nelectricity demand in 1999 was not followed by a similar increase of emissions\nbecause of the penetration of natural gas and the high availability of\nhydropower.\nThe majority of GHG emissions (47.43 %) in 2020 derived from energy\nindustries, while the contribution of transport, manufacturing industries and\nconstruction and other sectors is estimated at 29.75%, 8.63% and 12.76%\nrespectively. The rest 0.86% and 0.58% of total GHG emissions from Energy\nderived from fugitive emissions from fuels and other (mobile).\nWithin the fuel combustion activities, the only sector with increased emissions\ncompared to 1990 is transport, showing an increase of 5.78%. Emissions from\nenergy industries, manufacturing industries and construction and other sectors\n(i.e. residential, tertiary and agriculture sectors) had decreased by around\n47.43%, 52.64% and 23.90%, respectively, compared to 1990. The decrease in\nthe other sectors is noticeable during the recent years. Finally, fugitive emissions\nfrom fuels decreased by 63.48% for the period 1990 - 2020.\nIn total, GHG emissions from transport in 2020 increased by approximately\n5.5% compared to 1990 emissions (from 14.52 Mt CO2 eq in 1990 to 15.58 Mt\nCO2 eq in 2020). In 2020, the majority of GHG emissions derived from road\ntransport, the contribution of which increased from 83% in 1990 to\napproximately 86.96% of total emissions of the sector, as a result of two\ncontradictory parameters: a) the significant increase of the number of vehicles in\nthe country and b) the considerable progress in antipollution technology of the\nvehicles engines. The share of internal navigation in the emissions of the\ntransport sector fluctuated from 13% in 1990 to 11.46 % in 2020. Additionally,\ninternal aviation has a contribution of the order of 1.4% in 2020, while the\ncontribution of railways decreased from 1.4% in 1990 to less than 0.17% in\n2020. The contribution of other transport (pipeline transportation) is negligible.\nThe living standards improvement resulted in increase of passenger cars\nownership and transportation activity. The economic development of the period\n1990-2010 had a significant effect on the ownership ofpassenger cars. The\npassenger cars fleet was almost tripled compared to 1990 levels, while an\nincrease of the share of medium and larger size passenger vehicles is observed\n(from 27% in 1990, to 36% in 2008). In 1990, the number of passenger cars was\n1.7 million cars (1 car for every 6inhabitants), while in 2007 this figure reached\n4.8 million cars. Similar trends are also observed for the number of trucks, buses\nand motorcycles. This trend is shown to decelerate as aconsequence of the\neconomic crisis, although the percentage of car ownership in Greece is lower\nthan the EU average.\nHowever, negative impact on the GHG emmisions decrease in the period 2010-\n2020 has the age of passenger car fleet in Greece which increased due to the\neconomic crisis and the weakness of Greeks to replaced their old car (40 per cent capacity of the Cropland category on the one hand, and the increase of the sink\ncapacity of the Forest Land category on the other. 4 .\nUpstream exploration and exploitation of primary energy sources:\nEmissions from burning of natural gas and fuel oils for steam and other extra\nprocesses.\nFugitive emissions resulting from flaring during oil and gas production.\nFugitive emissions of methane during coal mining.\nTransformation of primary energy sources into more usable energy forms in refineries and p\nplants:\nEmissions from flaring and fuel combustion in refineries and power plants for s\nheat for use in process units and electricity generation.\nTransmission and distribution of fuels:\nFuel combustion to generate electrical power for pipelines.\nFuel combustion in transport trucks/vessels.\nFugitive emissions during transmission and distribution.\nUse of fuels in stationary and mobile applications:\nFuel combustion in the transport sector.\nOn-site power generation plants.\nIndustrial use for heat generation and to power equipment. 1 1 1 1 CCLW.gst.512.512 NIGERIA_NC3_18Apr2020_FINAL application/pdf False In Nigeria, fuel combustion activities and extraction of hydrocarbons are responsible for emissions of the\nEnergy sector, the contribution coming from the following activities: Nigeria is a producer and exporter of crude oil, petroleum products and natural gas. However, in recent\nyears, the country relied more on imports of petroleum products to meet its growing demand, especially\nwith the low performance of the local refineries. The main secondary sources of liquid, biomass and\ngaseous fuels are diesel, gasoline, LPG, kerosene, AGO/Diesel, ATK, fuel wood, charcoal, bagasse, vegetal\nwastes, natural gas and household kerosene (HHK) amongst others. Natural gas is utilized for public power\ngeneration with diesel and Fuel Oil (FO) as back-up fuels as well as in industries for heat and own-use\npower generation. Transport fuels include gasoline & AGO/Diesel for road transportation, inland water\nnavigation and railway, ATK for civil aviation and FO for international water navigation. Fuels consumed\nin the Commercial/Institutional and Residential sectors include HHK for cooking and lighting, LPG for\ncooking, gasoline and AGO/Diesel for auto-generation of electricity and other biomass fuels (fuel wood\nand charcoal). Table 2.9 presents the total consumption of primary and secondary fuels in the country for\nthe period 2000-2016. def plot_wordcloud(df, concept):
    # create wordclouds with title
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width = 800, height = 800,
                    background_color ='white',
                    stopwords = STOPWORDS,
                    min_font_size = 10).generate(' '.join(df.loc[df['type']==concept,'processed_text']))

    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 8), facecolor = None)
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.tight_layout(pad = 0)

    plt.show()
plot_wordcloud(df_spans, "GAS")
plot_wordcloud(df_spans, "OIL")

def find_country(text: str) -> str:
    """
    Given a text string, attempts to find the name of a country
    mentioned in the text. Returns the name of the country if found,
    or None otherwise.
    """
    # Check for uppercase and lowercase country name
    for country in pycountry.countries:
        if country.name.upper() in text.upper():
            return country.name
        elif country.name.lower() in text.lower():
            return country.name

    # Check for common name
    for country in pycountry.countries:
        if country.name in text:
            return country.name
        if hasattr(country, 'common_name') and country.common_name in text:
            return country.common_name

        # Check for official name
        if hasattr(country, 'official_name') and country.official_name in text:
            return country.official_name

        # Check for alpha_2 code (e.g., "US" for United States)
        if country.alpha_2 in re.findall(r'\b[A-Z]{2}\b', text):
            return country.name

        # Check for alpha_3 code (e.g., "USA" for United States)
        if country.alpha_3 in re.findall(r'\b[A-Z]{3}\b', text):
            return country.name

    return None


def get_country_code(x: str) -> str:
    """
    Given the name of a country, returns its ISO 3166-1 alpha-3
    code. Returns None if the country is not found.
    """
    try:
        return pycountry.countries.get(name=x).alpha_3
    except (AttributeError, LookupError):
        return None


# Create a new column 'country' with the found country names
df_concepts["document_name_x_reformatted"] = df_concepts["document_name_x"].str.replace(r'[_20]+', ' ', regex=True)
df_concepts["document_name_y_reformatted"] = df_concepts["document_name_y"].str.replace(r'[_20]+', ' ', regex=True)
df_concepts['country_x'] = df_concepts['document_name_x_reformatted'].apply(find_country)
df_concepts['country_y'] = df_concepts['document_name_y_reformatted'].apply(find_country)
df_concepts['country'] = df_concepts['country_x'].combine_first(df_concepts['country_y'])
# create 3 letter country code
df_concepts['country_code'] = df_concepts['country'].apply(get_country_code)

In [19]:
def create_docs_table(df_concepts):

    # First, create a new column that categorizes each row as 'Party' or 'Non-party'
    df_concepts['category'] = np.where(df_concepts['party'].notna(), 'Party', 'Non-party')

    # Use groupby to count the unique document_id's for each category and for the total dataset
    docs_analysed = df_concepts.groupby('category')['document_id'].nunique()
    docs_analysed.loc['Total'] = df_concepts['document_id'].nunique()

    # Convert the resulting Series into a DataFrame with a single row and a custom index
    docs_analysed_table = pd.DataFrame(docs_analysed.values.reshape(1, -1),
                                       columns=docs_analysed.index,
                                       index=["Documents"])

    return docs_analysed_table

docs_analysed_table = create_docs_table(df_concepts)
docs_analysed_table

from IPython.core.display_functions import display
from typing import Iterable

def get_cols_between(df: pd.DataFrame, start_col_name: str = "text", end_col_name: str = "document_id") -> Iterable[str]:
    """
    Get the names of the columns between two named columns in a dataframe.
    """
    start_col = df.columns.get_loc(start_col_name)
    end_col = df.columns.get_loc(end_col_name)
    assert start_col < end_col, "start_col must be before end_col"
    indicator_columns = df.columns[start_col + 1:end_col]
    return indicator_columns

def get_indicator_data(df: pd.DataFrame, indicator_col: str, value_col: str, category_col: str) -> List:
    """
    Get unique and total counts of a specific indicator column grouped by a category column.

    :param df: DataFrame containing the data.
    :param indicator_col: Column with the indicator values (1 or 0).
    :param value_col: Column used to count unique values.
    :param category_col: Column used to group the data.
    :return: List containing the indicator column and unique and total counts for each category and in total.
    """
    df_filtered = df[df[indicator_col] == 1]
    data_grouped = df_filtered.groupby(category_col)[value_col].agg(['nunique','count'])

    data_grouped.loc['Total'] = df_filtered[value_col].agg(['nunique', 'count'])


    result = [indicator_col, *data_grouped['nunique'], *data_grouped['count']]
    return result

def create_indicator_tables(df: pd.DataFrame, start_col_name, end_col_name: str, category_col: str, value_col: str) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    Create a table with unique and total counts for a range of indicator columns, grouped by a category column.

    :param df: DataFrame containing the data.
    :param category_col: Column used to group the data.
    :param start_col_name: Name of the last column before the indicator columns.
    :param end_col_name: Name of the first column after the indicator columns.
    :param value_col: Column used to count unique values.
    :return: DataFrame with unique and total counts for each indicator column and category.
    """
    indicator_cols = get_cols_between(df_concepts, start_col_name=start_col_name, end_col_name=end_col_name)
    data_list = [get_indicator_data(df, col, value_col, category_col) for col in indicator_cols]
    columns = ['Concept', 'Num Docs Mentioned (party)', 'Num Docs Mentioned (non-party)', 'Num Docs Mentioned (Total)', 'Num Concept Mentions (Parties)', 'Num Concept Mentions (Non-parties)', 'All Concept Mentions']
    return pd.DataFrame(data_list, columns=columns)

indicator_table = create_indicator_tables(df_concepts, start_col_name="text", end_col_name="document_id", category_col="category",value_col="document_id")

# Display the resulting DataFrames
print("Number of documents mentioning each concept.\n")

0 Methane mitigation opportunities by sector include:\n Energy Sector Methane. Energy sector fugitive methane emissions result from opera-\ntions in the oil and natural gas sector and the coal mining sector. In some cases, a large\nproportion of oil and gas methane emissions come from a small number of sources. Me-\nthane mitigation measures in oil and natural gas typically fall into three categories:\nequipment modifications or upgrades; changes in operational practices, including di-\nrected inspection, repair and maintenance (DI&M); and installation of new equipment\n[35]. Abatement measures are available to mitigate emissions associated with a variety\nof system components, including compressors, engines, dehydrators, pneumatic con-\ntrols, pipelines, storage tanks, wells, and others. Commercially-available mitigation tech-\nnologies can also recover and reduce CH4 emissions from coal mining operations. These\nreduction technologies consist of one or more of the following primary components: a\ndrainage and recovery system to remove CH4 from the underground coal seam, an end\nuse application for the gas recovered from the drainage system, and/or a ventilation air\nmethane (VAM) recovery or mitigation system [35]. The CH4 mitigation potential from\nthe energy sector at $100/tCOe is 144 million metric tons of carbon dioxide equivalent\n(MtCOe), or approximately 43% of 2030 energy sector non-CO GHG emissions, and re-\nmains an important source of potential mitigation through 2050.\n Waste Methane. Landfills produce CH4 and other landfill gases through the natural pro-\ncess of bacterial decomposition of organic waste under anaerobic conditions. Landfill\ngases are generated over a period of several decades, with flows usually beginning\nwithin 2 years of disposal. This figure does not include additional\nabatement that can be achieved by reducing the underlying activities that drive emis-\nsions. Approximately an addi-\ntional 125 MtCO2e can be abated at ~$50/tCO2e or less, primarily from oil and natural\ngas and livestock sources. Approximately an additional 50 MtCO2e can be abated at\n~$100/tCO2e or less, from livestock and oil and natural gas sources. A remaining ap-\nproximately 50 MtCO2e can only be abated at prices ~$150/tCO2e or higher. and (3) enhanced waste diversion practices (e.g., recycling and reuse programs) [35].\nWithin the waste category, wastewater treatment is the second most important source\nof non-CO GHGs. Methane emissions in wastewater treatment could be significantly\nreduced by 2050 through currently available mitigation options, such as anaerobic bio-\nmass digesters and centralized wastewater treatment facilities. Improved operational\npractices, such as controlling dissolved oxygen levels during treatment or limiting oper-\nating system upsets, can also help reduce NO emissions from wastewater treatment\n[35]. 1 processing activities. The extraction, production,\nprocessing, or transportation of fuels involve\nsubstantial quantity of methane emissions to the\natmosphere. Oil and natural gas systems are\npotentially very complex and diverse. Two major issues\nconcerning the reported fugitive emissions from oil\nand gas systems are: (i) the generally poor quality and\ncompleteness of available venting and flaring data; (ii)\nthe fact that much of the infrastructure contributing to\nequipment leaks is at minor facilities for which\nstatistics are either unavailable or incomplete (e.g.\nwell site facilities and field facilities). Fugitive\nemissions consist of CH, mostly however CO, is also\nemitted from the coal mines. It is the first time that the\ngovernment actually started to use coal for electricity\ngeneration. It was assumed that in 2017-18 most of the\ncoal mines were underground (80 %) and 20% coal was\nextracted from the surface mines. There are oil and gas\nproduction, processing, transmission and distribution\nactivities so around 3.29 Mt CO2e emission from oil and\ngas related infrastructure. Figure 2.4 shows the fugitive\nGHG emissions. 1 1 1 1 CCLW.gst.543.543 PakistanE28099s20First20Biennial20Update20Report2028BUR-12920-202022 application/pdf False The GHG emissions from this category in the energy\nsector have been divided further into two main sub-\ncategories: 1) Solid fuels (primarily coal mining), and 2)\nOil & natural gas systems. The dominant GHG emitted\nfrom all of these fugitive source categories is CH.. For\nsolid fuels, venting and disposal of coal- bed is the\nprimary source of fugitive emissions. 2 Upstream exploration and exploitation of primary energy sources:\nEmissions from exploration, mining and all related activities supporting the\nprocesses, products storage and transportation.\nFugitive emissions resulting from processes such as flaring, venting and lea\nconnecting and storage modules of crude oil and natural gas handling.\nFugitive emissions of methane during coal mining.\nTransformation of primary energy sources into more usable energy forms in refineries\nplants:\nEmissions from flaring, cracking of crude oil into component fractions an\ncombustion to support these activities. It also involves fuel combustions\nplants for steam, heat for use in electricity generation.\nTransmission and distribution of fuels:\nFuel combustion to generate electrical power for pipelines.\nFuel combustion in transport trucks / vessels.\nFugitive emissions during transmission and distribution.\nUse of fuels in stationary and mobile applications:\nFuel combustion in the transport sector.\nOn-site power generation plants.\nIndustrial use for heat generation and to power equipment. 1 1 1 1 CCLW.gst.511.511 NIGERIA20NIR120-20First20National20GHG20Inventory20Report20 application/pdf False The activities within the Energy sector, leading to these emissions occur in the different segments of\nactivities. Emissions are associated with energy production, processing for converting primary fuels into\nsecondary fuels, transportation and storage as well as end products utilization. Fuel combustion activities\nis one of such end products utilization and involves both primary and secondary fuels. Upstream to these\nare extraction, refining, transportation and storage of primary and secondary hydrocarbons. The activities\nresponsible for emissions are: Nigeria is a producer and exporter of crude oil, petroleum products and natural gas and produces coal for\ndomestic use. Whenever local production cannot meet local demand, the country resort to importation\nto bridge the gap between demand and supply. The main secondary sources of liquid, biomass and\ngaseous fuels are diesel, gasoline, Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG), kerosene, Automotive Gas Oil (AGO) /\nDiesel, Aviation Turbine Kerosene (ATK), fuel wood, charcoal, bagasse, vegetal wastes, natural gas and\nhousehold kerosene (HHK) amongst others. Natural gas is utilized for public power generation with diesel\nand Fuel Oil (FO) as back-up fuels as well as in industries for heat and own-use power generation.\nTransport fuels include gasoline and AGO / Diesel for road transportation, inland water navigation and\nrailway, ATK for civil aviation and FO for international water navigation. Fuels consumed in the\nCommercial / Institutional and Residential sectors include HHK for cooking and lighting, LPG for cooking,\ngasoline and AGO / Diesel for auto-generation of electricity and biomass fuels (fuel wood and charcoal). 3 of passenger cars are more than 20 years old). This phenomenon was aggravated\nmore by the high taxation imposed on vehicles with engines over 2000 cm.\nFugitive emissions from coal mining and handling (CH4 emissions) are a key\ncategory. CH4 emissions from the mining of lignite in 2020 account for 0.4% of\ntotal GHG emissions. A 72.9% decrease for the period 1990-2020 is observed.\nThis decrease is attributed to the gradual phasing-out of lignite-fired power\nplants in recent years. According to the NECP of Greece, there is an undergoing\nplan for the phasing-out of all but one lignite-plants by 2023. The remaining\nplant will be converted to NG by 2028.\nGHG emissions from activities related to primary production (extraction),\nprocessing, storage and transmission/ distribution of crude oil, petroleum\nproducts and natural gas included in Fugitive emissions, in 2020 accounted for\n0.26% of total GHG emissions. Overall, emissions in 2020 increased by about\n71.2% compared to 1990 levels. The parameters affecting GHG emissions trends\nfrom oil and natural gas are the gradual penetration of natural gas in the Greek\nenergy system and the domestic production of crude oil and natural gas. The\nintroduction of natural gas in the Greek energy system started in 1996 and at the\nmoment its development is in progress. The domestic production of crude oil and\nnatural gas present a continuous decreasing trend and as a result emissions from\nventing and flaring are decreasing.\nEmissions from Industrial Processes and Product use in 2020 accounted for\n14.01% of the total emissions (excluding LULUCF) and decreased by 7.02%\ncompared to 1990 levels. Emissions from IPPU are characterized by intense\nfluctuations during the period 1990 - 2020 reaching a minimum value of 10.39\nMt CO2 eq in 2011 and a maximum value of 16.41 Mt CO2 eq in 1999. The low\nvalue for 2011 is directly related to the effects of the economic recession\nwhereas the maximum value is attributed to changes in industrial production and\nespecially in HCFC-22 production. It should be noted that had it not been for the\nconsumption of f-gases subcategory, the decrease of the recent years would have\nbeen much deeper.\nEmissions from Agriculture that accounted for 10.48% of total emissions in\n2020 (without LULUCF), decreased by approximately 23.59% compared to\n1990 levels. Emissions reduction is mainly due to the reduction of N2O\nemissions from agricultural soils, because of the reduction in the use of synthetic\nnitrogen fertilizers and animal population. The decrease in the use of synthetic\nnitrogen fertilizers is attributed to the increase of organic farming, the high price\nof fertilizers and the impact of initiatives to promote good practice in fertilizer\nuse. The changes of the rest determining parameters of GHG emissions from the\nsector (e.g. crops production etc.) have a minor effect on GHG emissions trend.\nEmissions from the Waste Sector (6.52% of the total emissions, without\nLULUCF), increased by approximately 0.32% from 1990. Living standards\nimprovement resulted in an increase of the generated waste and thus of\nemissions since 1990. However, the increase of recycling along with the\nexploitation of the biogas produced limits the increase of methane emissions. At\nthe same time, emissions from wastewater handling have considerably\ndecreased, due to the continuous increase of the population served by aerobic\nwastewater handling facilities.\nThe Land Use, Land-Use Change and Forestry sector was a net sink of\ngreenhouse gases during the period 1990 - 2020. The sink capacity of the\nLULUCF sector fluctuates between -0.13 Mt CO2 eq. and -4.03 Mt CO2 eq.,\nshowing fluctuations in trend. This is the result of the decrease of the sink 1 1 1 1 CCLW.gst.508.508 NC8_BR5_Greece application/pdf False The living standards improvement resulted in an increase of energy consumption\nand particularly electricity consumption (mainly in the residential - tertiary\nsector), passenger cars ownership and transportation activity. The increase of\nelectricity consumption led not only to the increase of direct emissions (due to\ncombustion for electricity generation) but also of fugitive methane emissions\nfrom lignite mining.\nAt the same time total CO2 emissions per electricity produced have decreased\nmainly as a result of the introduction of the natural gas and RES into the\nelectricity system. It should be mentioned that the availability of hydropower has\na significant effect to emissions trends. For instance, the significant increase of\nelectricity demand in 1999 was not followed by a similar increase of emissions\nbecause of the penetration of natural gas and the high availability of\nhydropower.\nThe majority of GHG emissions (47.43 %) in 2020 derived from energy\nindustries, while the contribution of transport, manufacturing industries and\nconstruction and other sectors is estimated at 29.75%, 8.63% and 12.76%\nrespectively. The rest 0.86% and 0.58% of total GHG emissions from Energy\nderived from fugitive emissions from fuels and other (mobile).\nWithin the fuel combustion activities, the only sector with increased emissions\ncompared to 1990 is transport, showing an increase of 5.78%. Emissions from\nenergy industries, manufacturing industries and construction and other sectors\n(i.e. residential, tertiary and agriculture sectors) had decreased by around\n47.43%, 52.64% and 23.90%, respectively, compared to 1990. The decrease in\nthe other sectors is noticeable during the recent years. Finally, fugitive emissions\nfrom fuels decreased by 63.48% for the period 1990 - 2020.\nIn total, GHG emissions from transport in 2020 increased by approximately\n5.5% compared to 1990 emissions (from 14.52 Mt CO2 eq in 1990 to 15.58 Mt\nCO2 eq in 2020). In 2020, the majority of GHG emissions derived from road\ntransport, the contribution of which increased from 83% in 1990 to\napproximately 86.96% of total emissions of the sector, as a result of two\ncontradictory parameters: a) the significant increase of the number of vehicles in\nthe country and b) the considerable progress in antipollution technology of the\nvehicles engines. The share of internal navigation in the emissions of the\ntransport sector fluctuated from 13% in 1990 to 11.46 % in 2020. Additionally,\ninternal aviation has a contribution of the order of 1.4% in 2020, while the\ncontribution of railways decreased from 1.4% in 1990 to less than 0.17% in\n2020. The contribution of other transport (pipeline transportation) is negligible.\nThe living standards improvement resulted in increase of passenger cars\nownership and transportation activity. The economic development of the period\n1990-2010 had a significant effect on the ownership ofpassenger cars. The\npassenger cars fleet was almost tripled compared to 1990 levels, while an\nincrease of the share of medium and larger size passenger vehicles is observed\n(from 27% in 1990, to 36% in 2008). In 1990, the number of passenger cars was\n1.7 million cars (1 car for every 6inhabitants), while in 2007 this figure reached\n4.8 million cars. Similar trends are also observed for the number of trucks, buses\nand motorcycles. This trend is shown to decelerate as aconsequence of the\neconomic crisis, although the percentage of car ownership in Greece is lower\nthan the EU average.\nHowever, negative impact on the GHG emmisions decrease in the period 2010-\n2020 has the age of passenger car fleet in Greece which increased due to the\neconomic crisis and the weakness of Greeks to replaced their old car (40 per cent capacity of the Cropland category on the one hand, and the increase of the sink\ncapacity of the Forest Land category on the other. 4 .\nUpstream exploration and exploitation of primary energy sources:\nEmissions from burning of natural gas and fuel oils for steam and other extra\nprocesses.\nFugitive emissions resulting from flaring during oil and gas production.\nFugitive emissions of methane during coal mining.\nTransformation of primary energy sources into more usable energy forms in refineries and p\nplants:\nEmissions from flaring and fuel combustion in refineries and power plants for s\nheat for use in process units and electricity generation.\nTransmission and distribution of fuels:\nFuel combustion to generate electrical power for pipelines.\nFuel combustion in transport trucks/vessels.\nFugitive emissions during transmission and distribution.\nUse of fuels in stationary and mobile applications:\nFuel combustion in the transport sector.\nOn-site power generation plants.\nIndustrial use for heat generation and to power equipment. 1 1 1 1 CCLW.gst.512.512 NIGERIA_NC3_18Apr2020_FINAL application/pdf False In Nigeria, fuel combustion activities and extraction of hydrocarbons are responsible for emissions of the\nEnergy sector, the contribution coming from the following activities: Nigeria is a producer and exporter of crude oil, petroleum products and natural gas. However, in recent\nyears, the country relied more on imports of petroleum products to meet its growing demand, especially\nwith the low performance of the local refineries. The main secondary sources of liquid, biomass and\ngaseous fuels are diesel, gasoline, LPG, kerosene, AGO/Diesel, ATK, fuel wood, charcoal, bagasse, vegetal\nwastes, natural gas and household kerosene (HHK) amongst others. Natural gas is utilized for public power\ngeneration with diesel and Fuel Oil (FO) as back-up fuels as well as in industries for heat and own-use\npower generation. Transport fuels include gasoline & AGO/Diesel for road transportation, inland water\nnavigation and railway, ATK for civil aviation and FO for international water navigation. Fuels consumed\nin the Commercial/Institutional and Residential sectors include HHK for cooking and lighting, LPG for\ncooking, gasoline and AGO/Diesel for auto-generation of electricity and other biomass fuels (fuel wood\nand charcoal). Table 2.9 presents the total consumption of primary and secondary fuels in the country for\nthe period 2000-2016. # Convert the dataframe to a long format. The indicator columns will be converted to rows such that when the indicator is 1, the column name will be the concept name and  the values for the other columns will be duplicated if they are not unique.
df_concepts_melted = df_concepts.melt(id_vars=[col for col in df_concepts if col not in indicator_columns], value_vars=indicator_columns, var_name='concept', value_name='indicator')
In [43]:
# Filter the dataframe to only include rows where the indicator is 1
df_concepts_filtered = df_concepts_melted[df_concepts_melted['indicator'] == 1]

0 Methane mitigation opportunities by sector include:\n Energy Sector Methane. Energy sector fugitive methane emissions result from opera-\ntions in the oil and natural gas sector and the coal mining sector. In some cases, a large\nproportion of oil and gas methane emissions come from a small number of sources. Me-\nthane mitigation measures in oil and natural gas typically fall into three categories:\nequipment modifications or upgrades; changes in operational practices, including di-\nrected inspection, repair and maintenance (DI&M); and installation of new equipment\n[35]. Abatement measures are available to mitigate emissions associated with a variety\nof system components, including compressors, engines, dehydrators, pneumatic con-\ntrols, pipelines, storage tanks, wells, and others. Commercially-available mitigation tech-\nnologies can also recover and reduce CH4 emissions from coal mining operations. These\nreduction technologies consist of one or more of the following primary components: a\ndrainage and recovery system to remove CH4 from the underground coal seam, an end\nuse application for the gas recovered from the drainage system, and/or a ventilation air\nmethane (VAM) recovery or mitigation system [35]. The CH4 mitigation potential from\nthe energy sector at $100/tCOe is 144 million metric tons of carbon dioxide equivalent\n(MtCOe), or approximately 43% of 2030 energy sector non-CO GHG emissions, and re-\nmains an important source of potential mitigation through 2050.\n Waste Methane. Landfills produce CH4 and other landfill gases through the natural pro-\ncess of bacterial decomposition of organic waste under anaerobic conditions. Landfill\ngases are generated over a period of several decades, with flows usually beginning\nwithin 2 years of disposal. Abatement options to control landfill emissions are grouped\ninto three categories: (1) collection and flaring, (2) landfill gas (LFG) utilization systems, CCLW.gst.652.652 US_accessibleLTS2021 application/pdf False Figure 14: 2050 Methane Abatement Potential in the United States. This figure shows\nsources of methane abatement potential in 2030 in the United States [36]. This mar-\nginal abatement cost curve indicates the price at which methane mitigation from vari-\nous sources of methane are cost-effective. This figure does not include additional\nabatement that can be achieved by reducing the underlying activities that drive emis-\nsions. These additional reductions from activity driver changes are included in the GCAM\nmodeling and reflected in Figure 12. Approximately 100 MtCO2e in methane emissions\ncan be abated at negative cost, primarily from oil and natural gas sources, but also with\nsome contributions from coal mining, landfills, and livestock. Approximately an addi-\ntional 125 MtCO2e can be abated at ~$50/tCO2e or less, primarily from oil and natural\ngas and livestock sources. Approximately an additional 50 MtCO2e can be abated at\n~$100/tCO2e or less, from livestock and oil and natural gas sources. A remaining ap-\nproximately 50 MtCO2e can only be abated at prices ~$150/tCO2e or higher. and (3) enhanced waste diversion practices (e.g., recycling and reuse programs) [35].\nWithin the waste category, wastewater treatment is the second most important source\nof non-CO GHGs. 1 processing activities. The extraction, production,\nprocessing, or transportation of fuels involve\nsubstantial quantity of methane emissions to the\natmosphere. Oil and natural gas systems are\npotentially very complex and diverse. Two major issues\nconcerning the reported fugitive emissions from oil\nand gas systems are: (i) the generally poor quality and\ncompleteness of available venting and flaring data; (ii)\nthe fact that much of the infrastructure contributing to\nequipment leaks is at minor facilities for which\nstatistics are either unavailable or incomplete (e.g.\nwell site facilities and field facilities). Fugitive\nemissions consist of CH, mostly however CO, is also\nemitted from the coal mines. It is the first time that the\ngovernment actually started to use coal for electricity\ngeneration. It was assumed that in 2017-18 most of the\ncoal mines were underground (80 %) and 20% coal was\nextracted from the surface mines. There are oil and gas\nproduction, processing, transmission and distribution\nactivities so around 3.29 Mt CO2e emission from oil and\ngas related infrastructure. Figure 2.4 shows the fugitive\nGHG emissions. Biennial update report (BUR). BUR1. Pakistan Pakistan Pakistan PAK PAK SAS Party Gas 1
2 Upstream exploration and exploitation of primary energy sources:\nEmissions from exploration, mining and all related activities supporting the\nprocesses, products storage and transportation.\nFugitive emissions resulting from processes such as flaring, venting and lea\nconnecting and storage modules of crude oil and natural gas handling.\nFugitive emissions of methane during coal mining.\nTransformation of primary energy sources into more usable energy forms in refineries\nplants:\nEmissions from flaring, cracking of crude oil into component fractions an\ncombustion to support these activities. It also involves fuel combustions\nplants for steam, heat for use in electricity generation.\nTransmission and distribution of fuels:\nFuel combustion to generate electrical power for pipelines.\nFuel combustion in transport trucks / vessels.\nFugitive emissions during transmission and distribution.\nUse of fuels in stationary and mobile applications:\nFuel combustion in the transport sector.\nOn-site power generation plants.\nIndustrial use for heat generation and to power equipment. CCLW.gst.511.511 NIGERIA20NIR120-20First20National20GHG20Inventory20Report20 application/pdf False The activities within the Energy sector, leading to these emissions occur in the different segments of\nactivities. Emissions are associated with energy production, processing for converting primary fuels into\nsecondary fuels, transportation and storage as well as end products utilization. Fuel combustion activities\nis one of such end products utilization and involves both primary and secondary fuels. Upstream to these\nare extraction, refining, transportation and storage of primary and secondary hydrocarbons. The activities\nresponsible for emissions are: Nigeria is a producer and exporter of crude oil, petroleum products and natural gas and produces coal for\ndomestic use. Whenever local production cannot meet local demand, the country resort to importation\nto bridge the gap between demand and supply. The main secondary sources of liquid, biomass and\ngaseous fuels are diesel, gasoline, Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG), kerosene, Automotive Gas Oil (AGO) /\nDiesel, Aviation Turbine Kerosene (ATK), fuel wood, charcoal, bagasse, vegetal wastes, natural gas and\nhousehold kerosene (HHK) amongst others. Natural gas is utilized for public power generation with diesel\nand Fuel Oil (FO) as back-up fuels as well as in industries for heat and own-use power generation.\nTransport fuels include gasoline and AGO / Diesel for road transportation, inland water navigation and\nrailway, ATK for civil aviation and FO for international water navigation. Fuels consumed in the\nCommercial / Institutional and Residential sectors include HHK for cooking and lighting, LPG for cooking,\ngasoline and AGO / Diesel for auto-generation of electricity and biomass fuels (fuel wood and charcoal). 3 of passenger cars are more than 20 years old). This phenomenon was aggravated\nmore by the high taxation imposed on vehicles with engines over 2000 cm.\nFugitive emissions from coal mining and handling (CH4 emissions) are a key\ncategory. CH4 emissions from the mining of lignite in 2020 account for 0.4% of\ntotal GHG emissions. A 72.9% decrease for the period 1990-2020 is observed.\nThis decrease is attributed to the gradual phasing-out of lignite-fired power\nplants in recent years. According to the NECP of Greece, there is an undergoing\nplan for the phasing-out of all but one lignite-plants by 2023. The remaining\nplant will be converted to NG by 2028.\nGHG emissions from activities related to primary production (extraction),\nprocessing, storage and transmission/ distribution of crude oil, petroleum\nproducts and natural gas included in Fugitive emissions, in 2020 accounted for\n0.26% of total GHG emissions. Overall, emissions in 2020 increased by about\n71.2% compared to 1990 levels. The parameters affecting GHG emissions trends\nfrom oil and natural gas are the gradual penetration of natural gas in the Greek\nenergy system and the domestic production of crude oil and natural gas. The\nintroduction of natural gas in the Greek energy system started in 1996 and at the\nmoment its development is in progress. The domestic production of crude oil and\nnatural gas present a continuous decreasing trend and as a result emissions from\nventing and flaring are decreasing.\nEmissions from Industrial Processes and Product use in 2020 accounted for\n14.01% of the total emissions (excluding LULUCF) and decreased by 7.02%\ncompared to 1990 levels. Emissions from IPPU are characterized by intense\nfluctuations during the period 1990 - 2020 reaching a minimum value of 10.39\nMt CO2 eq in 2011 and a maximum value of 16.41 Mt CO2 eq in 1999. The low\nvalue for 2011 is directly related to the effects of the economic recession\nwhereas the maximum value is attributed to changes in industrial production and\nespecially in HCFC-22 production. It should be noted that had it not been for the\nconsumption of f-gases subcategory, the decrease of the recent years would have\nbeen much deeper.\nEmissions from Agriculture that accounted for 10.48% of total emissions in\n2020 (without LULUCF), decreased by approximately 23.59% compared to\n1990 levels. Emissions reduction is mainly due to the reduction of N2O\nemissions from agricultural soils, because of the reduction in the use of synthetic\nnitrogen fertilizers and animal population. The decrease in the use of synthetic\nnitrogen fertilizers is attributed to the increase of organic farming, the high price\nof fertilizers and the impact of initiatives to promote good practice in fertilizer\nuse. The changes of the rest determining parameters of GHG emissions from the\nsector (e.g. crops production etc.) have a minor effect on GHG emissions trend.\nEmissions from the Waste Sector (6.52% of the total emissions, without\nLULUCF), increased by approximately 0.32% from 1990. Living standards\nimprovement resulted in an increase of the generated waste and thus of\nemissions since 1990. However, the increase of recycling along with the\nexploitation of the biogas produced limits the increase of methane emissions. At\nthe same time, emissions from wastewater handling have considerably\ndecreased, due to the continuous increase of the population served by aerobic\nwastewater handling facilities.\nThe Land Use, Land-Use Change and Forestry sector was a net sink of\ngreenhouse gases during the period 1990 - 2020. The sink capacity of the\nLULUCF sector fluctuates between -0.13 Mt CO2 eq. and -4.03 Mt CO2 eq.,\nshowing fluctuations in trend. This is the result of the decrease of the sink CCLW.gst.508.508 NC8_BR5_Greece application/pdf False The living standards improvement resulted in an increase of energy consumption\nand particularly electricity consumption (mainly in the residential - tertiary\nsector), passenger cars ownership and transportation activity. The increase of\nelectricity consumption led not only to the increase of direct emissions (due to\ncombustion for electricity generation) but also of fugitive methane emissions\nfrom lignite mining.\nAt the same time total CO2 emissions per electricity produced have decreased\nmainly as a result of the introduction of the natural gas and RES into the\nelectricity system. It should be mentioned that the availability of hydropower has\na significant effect to emissions trends. For instance, the significant increase of\nelectricity demand in 1999 was not followed by a similar increase of emissions\nbecause of the penetration of natural gas and the high availability of\nhydropower.\nThe majority of GHG emissions (47.43 %) in 2020 derived from energy\nindustries, while the contribution of transport, manufacturing industries and\nconstruction and other sectors is estimated at 29.75%, 8.63% and 12.76%\nrespectively. The rest 0.86% and 0.58% of total GHG emissions from Energy\nderived from fugitive emissions from fuels and other (mobile).\nWithin the fuel combustion activities, the only sector with increased emissions\ncompared to 1990 is transport, showing an increase of 5.78%. Emissions from\nenergy industries, manufacturing industries and construction and other sectors\n(i.e. residential, tertiary and agriculture sectors) had decreased by around\n47.43%, 52.64% and 23.90%, respectively, compared to 1990. The decrease in\nthe other sectors is noticeable during the recent years. Finally, fugitive emissions\nfrom fuels decreased by 63.48% for the period 1990 - 2020.\nIn total, GHG emissions from transport in 2020 increased by approximately\n5.5% compared to 1990 emissions (from 14.52 Mt CO2 eq in 1990 to 15.58 Mt\nCO2 eq in 2020). In 2020, the majority of GHG emissions derived from road\ntransport, the contribution of which increased from 83% in 1990 to\napproximately 86.96% of total emissions of the sector, as a result of two\ncontradictory parameters: a) the significant increase of the number of vehicles in\nthe country and b) the considerable progress in antipollution technology of the\nvehicles engines. The share of internal navigation in the emissions of the\ntransport sector fluctuated from 13% in 1990 to 11.46 % in 2020. Additionally,\ninternal aviation has a contribution of the order of 1.4% in 2020, while the\ncontribution of railways decreased from 1.4% in 1990 to less than 0.17% in\n2020. The contribution of other transport (pipeline transportation) is negligible.\nThe living standards improvement resulted in increase of passenger cars\nownership and transportation activity. The economic development of the period\n1990-2010 had a significant effect on the ownership ofpassenger cars. The\npassenger cars fleet was almost tripled compared to 1990 levels, while an\nincrease of the share of medium and larger size passenger vehicles is observed\n(from 27% in 1990, to 36% in 2008). In 1990, the number of passenger cars was\n1.7 million cars (1 car for every 6inhabitants), while in 2007 this figure reached\n4.8 million cars. Similar trends are also observed for the number of trucks, buses\nand motorcycles. This trend is shown to decelerate as aconsequence of the\neconomic crisis, although the percentage of car ownership in Greece is lower\nthan the EU average.\nHowever, negative impact on the GHG emmisions decrease in the period 2010-\n2020 has the age of passenger car fleet in Greece which increased due to the\neconomic crisis and the weakness of Greeks to replaced their old car (40 per cent capacity of the Cropland category on the one hand, and the increase of the sink\ncapacity of the Forest Land category on the other. 4 .\nUpstream exploration and exploitation of primary energy sources:\nEmissions from burning of natural gas and fuel oils for steam and other extra\nprocesses.\nFugitive emissions resulting from flaring during oil and gas production.\nFugitive emissions of methane during coal mining.\nTransformation of primary energy sources into more usable energy forms in refineries and p\nplants:\nEmissions from flaring and fuel combustion in refineries and power plants for s\nheat for use in process units and electricity generation.\nTransmission and distribution of fuels:\nFuel combustion to generate electrical power for pipelines.\nFuel combustion in transport trucks/vessels.\nFugitive emissions during transmission and distribution.\nUse of fuels in stationary and mobile applications:\nFuel combustion in the transport sector.\nOn-site power generation plants.\nIndustrial use for heat generation and to power equipment. CCLW.gst.512.512 NIGERIA_NC3_18Apr2020_FINAL application/pdf False In Nigeria, fuel combustion activities and extraction of hydrocarbons are responsible for emissions of the\nEnergy sector, the contribution coming from the following activities: Nigeria is a producer and exporter of crude oil, petroleum products and natural gas. However, in recent\nyears, the country relied more on imports of petroleum products to meet its growing demand, especially\nwith the low performance of the local refineries. The main secondary sources of liquid, biomass and\ngaseous fuels are diesel, gasoline, LPG, kerosene, AGO/Diesel, ATK, fuel wood, charcoal, bagasse, vegetal\nwastes, natural gas and household kerosene (HHK) amongst others. Natural gas is utilized for public power\ngeneration with diesel and Fuel Oil (FO) as back-up fuels as well as in industries for heat and own-use\npower generation. Transport fuels include gasoline & AGO/Diesel for road transportation, inland water\nnavigation and railway, ATK for civil aviation and FO for international water navigation. Fuels consumed\nin the Commercial/Institutional and Residential sectors include HHK for cooking and lighting, LPG for\ncooking, gasoline and AGO/Diesel for auto-generation of electricity and other biomass fuels (fuel wood\nand charcoal). Table 2.9 presents the total consumption of primary and secondary fuels in the country for\nthe period 2000-2016. from vega_datasets import data
import geopandas as gpd
world_map = alt.topo_feature(data.world_110m.url, "countries")


# Aggregate the data
agg_df = df_concepts_filtered.groupby("region").size().reset_index(name="mentions")

# Define the region codes
region_codes = {"NAC": "North America", "SAS": "South America", "SSF": "Sub-Saharan Africa", "ECS": "Eastern Europe"}

# Map the region codes to their respective names
agg_df["region_name"] = agg_df["region"].map(region_codes)

# Load the GeoDataFrame from the world dataset
world = gpd.read_file(gpd.datasets.get_path("naturalearth_lowres"))

# Merge the world GeoDataFrame with the aggregated data
merged = world.set_index("continent").join(agg_df.set_index("region_name"), how="inner")

# Create the choropleth map
choropleth_map = (
    alt.Chart(merged)
    .mark_geoshape(stroke="black", strokeWidth=1)
    .encode(
        color=alt.Color("mentions:Q", scale=alt.Scale(scheme="viridis")),
        tooltip=["continent:N", "mentions:Q"],
    )
    .properties(width=800, height=400, title="Number of Mentions of {} by Region")
)

choropleth_map.display()
